# Expo and EAS Mobile Workflow Rules

## Intent
Enable reliable React Native Android development without Android Studio or local emulator dependency.

## Operating Assumption
- Primary mobile workflow is cloud-first using Expo + EAS.
- Local machine may be low-power and used mainly for code edits, commits, and basic checks.

## Mandatory Platform Strategy
- Use Expo-managed workflow by default for `packages/mobile`.
- Use EAS Build for all installable Android builds (preview, staging, production).
- Use EAS Update for JavaScript/asset-only updates.
- Any native dependency/config change requires a new EAS build before validation.

## Required Environments and Channels
- Define build profiles at minimum: `preview`, `staging`, `production`.
- Define update channels at minimum: `preview`, `staging`, `production`.
- Map Git branches to update channels explicitly; avoid implicit branch/channel drift.

## Release and Testing Flow
- For pull requests affecting mobile code, generate a preview Android APK via EAS Build.
- Test preview build on physical Android devices before merge for critical journeys.
- Production release must generate signed APK and publish via GitHub Releases.
- Keep AAB optional; APK remains mandatory for user distribution.

## OTA Update Safety Rules
- Use runtime version policy so incompatible native/runtime updates are blocked.
- Use code signing for EAS updates.
- Require rollback path for every production update.
- Do not ship OTA updates that change behavior requiring new native permissions/config.

## Configuration and Secrets
- Keep Expo config in source control with environment-specific configuration.
- Store signing credentials and secrets in secure managed stores (EAS/GitHub environments).
- Never commit signing keys or raw secret values.

## CI Integration Requirements
- GitHub Actions must orchestrate EAS preview and release builds.
- CI must annotate PRs with install links or artifact locations for preview builds.
- CI must block release if preview/staging validation rules fail.

## Performance and Reliability
- Enable instrumentation early for startup time, navigation latency, JS thread load, and memory.
- Set practical asset-size budgets and image optimization to reduce low-end device pressure.

## Prohibited
- Requiring Android Studio/local emulator as the only validation path.
- Shipping mobile changes without a device-testable build artifact.
- Using unmanaged ad-hoc OTA pushes without channel and rollback discipline.